## M3.S4 — Single-Owner Rule

`M3.S4.C1` Each canonical handoff has exactly one owner phase.

`M3.S4.C2` The owner phase is responsible for:

a. constructing the handoff;
b. applying the relevant Field Canon rules;
c. following the Contract Spine object shape;
d. preserving evidence references;
e. recording limitations and unknowns;
f. emitting the handoff under the authorized canonical name;
g. producing the required phase forensic ledger;
h. producing the required phase forensic trace where required;
i. validating required fields before lock;
j. marking the handoff lifecycle state.

`M3.S4.C3` No non-owner phase may create, replace, rename, or overwrite another phase’s canonical handoff.

`M3.S4.C4` A downstream phase may consume a locked upstream handoff but must not mutate it.

`M3.S4.C5` If a downstream phase detects a material upstream defect, it must mark the defect and route to repair, reinvestigation, limitation, or controlled failure.

---

## M3.S5 — Handoff Lock Rule

`M3.S5.C1` A handoff is not locked merely because a model emitted it.

`M3.S5.C2` A handoff becomes locked only when all of the following are true:

a. it is emitted by its owner phase;
b. it uses the authorized canonical handoff name;
c. it follows the Contract Spine object shape;
d. all required fields are present or validly empty under Field Canon rules;
e. controlled values are valid;
f. evidence references are structurally valid;
g. factual assertions trace to admitted evidence, documented absence, synthetic/demo material, or locked upstream handoffs;
h. required limitations are recorded;
i. no forbidden source material is used;
j. no phase-power violation is present;
k. required forensic trace is present where required;
l. server validation passes or records only permitted warning-level defects;
m. handoff lifecycle state is marked `LOCKED` or `LOCKED_WITH_LIMITATIONS`.

`M3.S5.C3` A complete-looking handoff that fails evidence law is invalid.

`M3.S5.C4` A schema-valid handoff that lacks required provenance is invalid.

`M3.S5.C5` A handoff with valid field names but undefined field meaning is invalid.

`M3.S5.C6` A handoff emitted by the wrong phase is invalid.

---

## M3.S6 — Retained Handoff / Runtime Memory Rule

`M3.S6.C1` Once locked, a canonical handoff becomes retained runtime memory for the current run.

`M3.S6.C2` Retained runtime memory is phase-bound, run-bound, and evidence-bound.

`M3.S6.C3` Retained runtime memory must not be confused with model memory, prior runs, training data, assumptions, or external recollection.

`M3.S6.C4` Downstream phases must consume retained handoffs as locked inputs, not as suggestions.

`M3.S6.C5` A downstream phase must not re-derive an upstream handoff from raw evidence unless the Runtime Spine or owner-phase repair path expressly requires reopening the owner phase.

`M3.S6.C6` If token limits require compact handoff references, the full locked handoff must remain preserved in run state.

`M3.S6.C7` If a retained handoff is unavailable, corrupted, incomplete, or inaccessible, the system must mark handoff memory failure rather than recreate it from memory.

---

## M3.S7 — Handoff Mutation Bar

`M3.S7.C1` A locked handoff must not be changed by downstream phases.

`M3.S7.C2` A downstream phase may:

a. read a locked handoff;
b. cite it as an upstream source;
c. map it into its own authorized handoff;
d. preserve its limitations;
e. identify a defect or limitation;
f. request repair, reinvestigation, limitation, or controlled failure.

`M3.S7.C3` A downstream phase may not:

a. silently correct an upstream field;
b. overwrite an upstream field;
c. rename an upstream field;
d. fill missing upstream facts;
e. soften upstream limitations;
f. delete uncertainty;
g. convert a warning into a fact;
h. convert insufficient evidence into positive evidence;
i. mutate a locked upstream handoff to make its own output easier;
j. replace the upstream handoff with a summary;
k. treat a downstream inference as an upstream fact.

`M3.S7.C4` If a locked handoff is materially defective, the system must reopen the owner phase through an approved repair path or enter controlled failure.

---

## M3.S8 — Evidence Reference Survival Rule

`M3.S8.C1` Every canonical handoff field that asserts a company fact, product fact, feature/function fact, legal/governance observation, data-provenance observation, exposure condition, registry condition, limitation, or final report statement must trace to one of the following:

a. admitted evidence;
b. documented absence;
c. clearly labeled synthetic/demo material;
d. a locked upstream handoff that itself traces to admitted evidence, documented absence, or synthetic/demo material.

`M3.S8.C2` Evidence references may be compact for model efficiency, but they must point back to the lossless Evidence Box.

`M3.S8.C3` A locked handoff does not break the evidence chain; it carries the evidence chain forward.

`M3.S8.C4` A downstream phase may rely on an upstream handoff only to the extent the upstream handoff preserves valid evidence references, documented absence records, synthetic/demo labels, and limitations.

`M3.S8.C5` Rejected, quarantined, inaccessible, private, third-party, or unreviewed material must not be cited as proof inside any handoff.

`M3.S8.C6` If the evidence chain cannot be resolved, the affected field must be marked as limitation, unknown, insufficient evidence, repair request, or controlled failure under the relevant Field Canon and phase prompt.

