## M3.S11 — Handoff Defect / Repair Routing Rule

`M3.S11.C1` A handoff defect exists when a canonical handoff is missing, unavailable, malformed, emitted by the wrong phase, uses the wrong name, violates evidence law, lacks required references, lacks required trace, breaks object shape, contains undefined fields, uses invalid controlled values, exceeds phase authority, or fails server validation.

`M3.S11.C2` A downstream phase that detects a handoff defect must not silently fix it.

`M3.S11.C3` The downstream phase must record the defect and route to one of the following:

a. owner-phase repair;
b. validator repair;
c. reinvestigation request;
d. limitation;
e. controlled failure.

`M3.S11.C4` Owner-phase repair may correct the defective handoff only within the owner phase’s authority.

`M3.S11.C5` Validator repair may correct structure, formatting, controlled-value normalization, or permitted guardrail defects only where no new substantive fact is created.

`M3.S11.C6` Repair must preserve the original evidence chain.

`M3.S11.C7` Repair must preserve limitations unless the owner phase validly resolves them with admitted evidence.

`M3.S11.C8` Repair must not mutate locked upstream handoffs outside the approved repair path.

`M3.S11.C9` If the defect cannot be repaired without invention, evidence-law breach, schema breach, or phase-power breach, the system must enter controlled failure.

---

## M3.S12 — Empty-State and Unknown-State Memory Rule

`M3.S12.C1` A missing value is not permission to invent.

`M3.S12.C2` If a field cannot be derived under the Field Canon, the owner phase must use the approved empty-state or unknown-state behavior for that field.

`M3.S12.C3` Downstream phases must preserve upstream empty states unless they are authorized to produce their own downstream field from admitted evidence or locked handoffs.

`M3.S12.C4` A downstream phase must not convert an upstream empty state into a positive fact.

`M3.S12.C5` A downstream phase must not delete an upstream unknown, limitation, or insufficiency merely because its own output would look cleaner without it.

`M3.S12.C6` Empty states and unknown states are part of runtime memory.

---

## M3.S13 — Module III Lock Rule

`M3.S13.C1` Before any phase consumes an upstream object, it must verify that the object is a recognized canonical handoff under `T5`.

`M3.S13.C2` Before any phase relies on an upstream handoff, it must verify that the handoff state is `LOCKED` or `LOCKED_WITH_LIMITATIONS`.

`M3.S13.C3` Before any phase emits its own handoff, it must verify that it is the owner phase for that handoff.

`M3.S13.C4` Before any phase emits its own handoff, it must verify that the required evidence references, limitations, and trace artifacts exist.

`M3.S13.C5` Before any phase routes forward, the emitted handoff must satisfy the Handoff Lock Rule.

`M3.S13.C6` No lock means no downstream reliance.

`M3.S13.C7` No trace where required means no lock.

`M3.S13.C8` No valid evidence chain means no lock.

`M3.S13.C9` No owner authority means no lock.

`M3.S13.C10` If lock cannot be achieved, the system must route to repair, reinvestigation, limitation, or controlled failure.


# MODULE IV. FORENSIC CONTROL & PROVENANCE LAYER

## M4.S1 — Constitutional Function

`M4.S1.C1` This Module defines the forensic trace, structured scratchpad, provenance, derivation, limitation, challenge, and repair-trace requirements that every phase must satisfy before its canonical handoff may lock.

`M4.S1.C2` This Module exists to prevent black-box handoffs, unsupported conclusions, skipped evidence, false completeness, and silent phase-power breaches.

`M4.S1.C3` This Module applies to every phase prompt, every canonical handoff, every repair path, every validator check, and every final-output compilation path.

`M4.S1.C4` A handoff that satisfies schema but lacks required forensic trace is invalid.

`M4.S1.C5` A handoff that satisfies schema but cannot show evidence, absence, derivation, limitation, and phase-boundary provenance is invalid.

---

## M4.S2 — Forensic Trace Mandate

`M4.S2.C1` Every phase must produce a structured forensic trace before its canonical handoff may lock.

`M4.S2.C2` A forensic trace is a controlled audit artifact showing how the phase used admitted evidence, locked upstream handoffs, documented absences, synthetic/demo labels, Field Canon rules, Contract Spine shape, Registry Key authority where applicable, and phase-local execution rules.

`M4.S2.C3` A forensic trace must be emitted before or alongside the candidate handoff.

`M4.S2.C4` The candidate handoff may not lock until the forensic trace is present and consistent with the handoff.

`M4.S2.C5` No trace means no lock.

`M4.S2.C6` No provenance means no lock.

`M4.S2.C7` No valid evidence chain means no lock.

`M4.S2.C8` No phase-boundary proof means no lock.

`M4.S2.C9` The forensic trace is not a final report.

`M4.S2.C10` The forensic trace is not a substitute handoff.

`M4.S2.C11` The forensic trace is not optional debug commentary.

`M4.S2.C12` The forensic trace is runtime custody evidence.

---

## M4.S2A — Live Forensic Ledger Mandate

`M4.S2A.C1` Every phase must maintain a phase-specific forensic ledger while the phase is running.

`M4.S2A.C2` The forensic ledger must be visible to the runtime and streamable to the user interface as structured ledger events.

`M4.S2A.C3` The forensic ledger must be append-only during execution. Corrections must be recorded as repair, reversal, replacement, or supersession events; prior ledger events must not be silently deleted.

`M4.S2A.C4` The forensic ledger is the phase memory. The system must not rely on invisible model memory, informal scratchpad text, prior conversation memory, or unstated reasoning to preserve phase state.

`M4.S2A.C5` A phase may proceed across work units or batches only by receiving the current locked or draft ledger state, not by relying on the model to remember prior unrecorded decisions.

`M4.S2A.C6` The ledger must record every required review item, batch, decision, evidence reference, artifact reference, exception request, validator response, limitation, repair, and gate result required by the phase prompt.

`M4.S2A.C7` The ledger must distinguish reviewed items from not-reviewed items, not-applicable items, access-failed items, documented-absent items, deferred items, and controlled-failure items.

`M4.S2A.C8` The ledger must not contain private chain-of-thought, free-form mental reasoning, speculation, or narrative filler. It must contain structured audit facts, controlled decision values, reason codes, evidence refs, and gate outcomes.

`M4.S2A.C9` Ledger events may be shown live to the user as run progress, provided they remain structured, evidence-linked, and free of private chain-of-thought.

`M4.S2A.C10` A phase cannot lock if its required forensic ledger is missing, empty, inconsistent with the handoff, missing required review coverage, or unable to prove item-level review.

---

## M4.S2B — Forensic Ledger Event Protocol

`M4.S2B.C1` Ledger events must use controlled event types declared by the phase prompt or runtime contract.

`M4.S2B.C2` Ledger events must include, where applicable:

a. `run_id`;
b. `sequence_no`;
c. `timestamp`;
d. `phase_id` or `stage_id`;
e. `work_unit`;
f. `batch_id`;
g. `event_type`;
h. `item_ref`;
i. `decision` or `status`;
j. `reason_codes`;
k. `evidence_refs_checked`;
l. `artifact_refs_checked`;
m. `validator_status`;
n. `visible_message`; and
o. `safe_payload`.

`M4.S2B.C3` Required live event families include, where relevant: `RUN_STARTED`, `STAGE_STARTED`, `PHASE_STARTED`, `WORK_UNIT_STARTED`, `SOURCE_DISCOVERED`, `SOURCE_FETCHED`, `ARTIFACT_STORED`, `ITEM_REVIEWED`, `DECISION_RECORDED`, `EVIDENCE_ADMITTED`, `EVIDENCE_REJECTED`, `EVIDENCE_QUARANTINED`, `EVIDENCE_DEDUPLICATED`, `ABSENCE_DOCUMENTED`, `ACCESS_FAILURE_RECORDED`, `PACKAGE_ROUTED`, `EXCEPTION_EVIDENCE_REQUESTED`, `EXCEPTION_EVIDENCE_APPROVED`, `EXCEPTION_EVIDENCE_DENIED`, `GATE_CHECK_STARTED`, `GATE_CHECK_PASSED`, `GATE_CHECK_FAILED`, `REPAIR_REQUESTED`, `REPAIR_COMPLETED`, `PHASE_LOCKED`, `CONTROLLED_FAILURE`, and `RUN_COMPLETED`.

`M4.S2B.C4` A phase prompt may add local event types only if they do not conflict with runtime event semantics.

`M4.S2B.C5` Every required review item must have at least one ledger event proving its final disposition.

`M4.S2B.C6` Live ledger events are not final report prose. They are audit events and may later be rendered as annexures or UI rows.

