## M4.S5 — Provenance Minimums

`M4.S5.C1` Every forensic trace must identify the active phase.

`M4.S5.C2` Every forensic trace must identify the canonical handoff being prepared.

`M4.S5.C3` Every forensic trace must identify locked upstream handoffs consumed.

`M4.S5.C4` Every forensic trace must identify admitted evidence references used.

`M4.S5.C5` Every forensic trace must identify documented absence records used.

`M4.S5.C6` Every forensic trace must identify synthetic/demo material used, if any.

`M4.S5.C7` Every forensic trace must identify rejected, quarantined, inaccessible, or outside-scope material considered where relevant.

`M4.S5.C8` Every forensic trace must identify material limitations, source limitations, evidence limitations, and uncertainty states.

`M4.S5.C9` Every forensic trace must identify field derivation basis for material asserted fields.

`M4.S5.C10` Every forensic trace must identify phase-boundary checks.

`M4.S5.C11` Every forensic trace must identify whether the phase is ready to lock.

`M4.S5.C12` Every forensic trace must identify repair history if the handoff was repaired.

---

## M4.S6 — Evidence Use / Rejection / Absence Ledger

`M4.S6.C1` Every phase trace must distinguish evidence used from evidence merely collected.

`M4.S6.C2` Every phase trace must distinguish admitted evidence from rejected, quarantined, inaccessible, private, third-party, unreviewed, or outside-scope material.

`M4.S6.C3` Every phase trace must record evidence references used for material assertions.

`M4.S6.C4` Every phase trace must record rejected or quarantined references where those references were encountered and excluded.

`M4.S6.C5` Every phase trace must record documented absences relied upon by the phase.

`M4.S6.C6` A phase may not rely on absence unless the absence was searched, reviewed, ingested, or classified absent under the current run.

`M4.S6.C7` A phase may not treat access failure as substantive absence.

`M4.S6.C8` A phase may not treat collected but unadmitted material as evidence.

`M4.S6.C9` A phase may not treat evidence routed only to another phase as usable unless the phase package or active phase prompt expressly includes it.

`M4.S6.C10` If a phase did not review a relevant evidence category, it must record that limitation rather than imply full coverage.

---

## M4.S7 — Derivation Trail Rule

`M4.S7.C1` Every material asserted field must have a derivation basis.

`M4.S7.C2` A derivation basis must identify the admitted evidence, documented absence, synthetic/demo material, or locked upstream handoff supporting the field.

`M4.S7.C3` A derivation basis must not rely on unstated reasoning, model memory, industry assumptions, branding, product category, company category, or inference from similar companies.

`M4.S7.C4` A derivation basis may be concise, but it must be specific enough for validation.

`M4.S7.C5` A derivation basis must distinguish direct evidence from downstream mapping.

`M4.S7.C6` A derivation basis must distinguish visible facts from limitations, unknowns, and insufficient-evidence states.

`M4.S7.C7` For feature/function records, the derivation trail must show product wrapper context, atomic feature/function behaviour, evidence reference, and archetype/surface signal basis.

`M4.S7.C8` For legal cartography records, the derivation trail must show artifact type, document unit, evidence reference, visible text unit or structure basis, and absence basis where applicable.

`M4.S7.C9` For data provenance records, the derivation trail must show feature-linked data signal, legal/governance support where available, evidence reference, and uncertainty state.

`M4.S7.C10` For registry evaluation records, the derivation trail must show registry row, routing basis, evidence basis, absence basis where applicable, status basis, and limitation basis.

`M4.S7.C11` For final output records, the derivation trail must show which locked upstream handoff supplied the final-output statement.

---

## M4.S8 — Limitation and Uncertainty Carry-Forward Rule

`M4.S8.C1` Limitations are part of the evidence chain.

`M4.S8.C2` Unknown states are part of runtime memory.

`M4.S8.C3` Insufficient-evidence states are part of runtime memory.

`M4.S8.C4` Documented absences are part of runtime memory.

`M4.S8.C5` A downstream phase must preserve upstream limitations, unknowns, insufficient-evidence states, and documented absences unless the downstream phase is authorized to resolve them using admitted evidence or a locked upstream handoff.

`M4.S8.C6` A downstream phase must not delete, soften, hide, or convert limitations merely to produce a cleaner handoff.

`M4.S8.C7` A downstream phase must not convert insufficient evidence into positive evidence.

`M4.S8.C8` A downstream phase must not convert a documented absence into real-world nonexistence.

`M4.S8.C9` A downstream phase may add a downstream limitation if its own evidence package, trace, or phase authority is limited.

`M4.S8.C10` Final Output Handoff must carry forward material limitations and uncertainty states required for honest public-demo reporting.

---

## M4.S9 — Phase Boundary Proof Rule

`M4.S9.C1` Every forensic trace must include phase-boundary checks.

`M4.S9.C2` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase performed only its authorized job.

`M4.S9.C3` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase did not emit another phase’s canonical handoff.

`M4.S9.C4` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase did not mutate locked upstream handoffs.

`M4.S9.C5` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase did not create final report narrative unless expressly authorized by Final Output Handoff compiler structure.

`M4.S9.C6` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase did not assign registry statuses unless the active phase is `06_EXPOSURE_PROFILE_REGISTRY_LEDGER.md`.

`M4.S9.C7` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase did not use rejected, quarantined, private, unreviewed, or outside-scope material as proof.

`M4.S9.C8` Phase-boundary checks must confirm that the phase did not invent facts to satisfy schema.

`M4.S9.C9` A phase-boundary breach blocks handoff lock.

---

## M4.S10 — Operator Challenge Gate

`M4.S10.C1` Operator Challenge is a forensic control gate, not a separate canonical phase.

`M4.S10.C2` Operator Challenge may run after a phase trace, before handoff lock, during repair, or before Final Output Handoff locks.

`M4.S10.C3` Operator Challenge exists to detect:

a. skipped evidence;
b. source-family under-review;
c. suspiciously low findings;
d. impossible completeness;
e. unsupported assertions;
f. missing evidence references;
g. missing documented absence basis;
h. phase-power breaches;
i. upstream handoff mutation;
j. missing limitations;
k. registry row omissions;
l. uncontrolled vocabulary;
m. final compiler creating new analysis;
n. renderer or final-output drift.

`M4.S10.C4` Operator Challenge may not invent facts.

`M4.S10.C5` Operator Challenge may not create new conclusions.

`M4.S10.C6` Operator Challenge may not override governing references.

`M4.S10.C7` Operator Challenge may only challenge, flag, route to repair, route to reinvestigation, preserve limitation, or force controlled failure.

`M4.S10.C8` If Operator Challenge fails, the affected phase must reopen, repair, mark limitation, request reinvestigation, or enter controlled failure.

---

## M4.S11 — Repair Trace Rule

`M4.S11.C1` Every repair must produce or update a repair trace.

`M4.S11.C2` A repair trace must identify what failed.

`M4.S11.C3` A repair trace must identify the governing reference, clause, field rule, contract rule, registry rule, validator rule, or phase rule that required repair.

`M4.S11.C4` A repair trace must identify what changed.

`M4.S11.C5` A repair trace must identify what did not change.

`M4.S11.C6` A repair trace must identify whether any evidence reference, documented absence, limitation, field value, handoff state, or controlled value changed.

`M4.S11.C7` A repair trace must preserve the original evidence chain.

`M4.S11.C8` A repair trace must preserve limitations unless the owner phase validly resolves them with admitted evidence.

`M4.S11.C9` Repair must not launder hallucination into a passing handoff.

`M4.S11.C10` Repair must not convert unsupported assertions into supported assertions without admitted evidence, documented absence, synthetic/demo material, or locked upstream handoff basis.

`M4.S11.C11` Repair must not mutate locked upstream handoffs outside the approved repair path.

`M4.S11.C12` If repair cannot be completed without invention, evidence-law breach, schema breach, phase-power breach, or unauthorized mutation, the system must enter controlled failure.

---

## M4.S12 — Trace Retention and Display Boundary

`M4.S12.C1` Forensic ledgers and forensic traces must be retained as run artifacts.

`M4.S12.C2` Forensic ledgers and forensic traces may be used by validators, repair routines, operator review, final compiler checks, audit exports, live UI progress display, and final report annexures.

`M4.S12.C3` Forensic ledgers and forensic traces are not automatically public-facing report content, but ledger events may be shown live in the runtime UI as structured audit progress where the UI is designed for forensic visibility.

`M4.S12.C4` Final Output Handoff may include sanitized ledger views or trace summaries only where permitted by the Contract Spine and final-output prompt.

`M4.S12.C5` Renderer may display ledger-derived annexures, trace-derived limitations, citations, source coverage, and audit summaries only if carried by `final_output_handoff`.

`M4.S12.C6` Renderer must not expose raw ledger or trace content as final report reasoning unless expressly authorized by `final_output_handoff`; it may display ledger rows as audit annexure material without converting them into reasoning narrative.

---

## M4.S13 — Module IV Lock Rule

`M4.S13.C1` Before any canonical handoff locks, the required forensic ledger and required trace in `T8` must exist.

`M4.S13.C2` Before any canonical handoff locks, the forensic ledger and trace must be structured, fielded, and phase-specific.

`M4.S13.C3` Before any canonical handoff locks, the trace must identify upstream handoffs consumed and the forensic ledger must identify required review items and their final dispositions.

`M4.S13.C4` Before any canonical handoff locks, the trace must identify admitted evidence references, documented absences, synthetic/demo material, and limitations used.

`M4.S13.C5` Before any canonical handoff locks, the trace must identify material field derivation basis.

`M4.S13.C6` Before any canonical handoff locks, the trace must confirm phase-boundary compliance.

`M4.S13.C7` Before any canonical handoff locks, the trace must support the emitted handoff.

`M4.S13.C8` Before any canonical handoff locks, any repair must have a repair trace.

`M4.S13.C9` Before any canonical handoff locks, Operator Challenge must pass if invoked.

`M4.S13.C10` No forensic ledger means no lock.

`M4.S13.C11` No trace means no lock.

`M4.S13.C12` No provenance means no lock.

`M4.S13.C13` No valid evidence chain means no lock.

`M4.S13.C14` No phase-boundary proof means no lock.

`M4.S13.C15` No required-item ledger coverage means no lock.

`M4.S13.C16` If the Module IV Lock Rule cannot be satisfied, the system must route to repair, reinvestigation, limitation, or controlled failure.


# MODULE V. PHASE CONTROL MATRIX — INSTITUTIONAL POWERS & FORBIDDEN ACTS

## M5.S1 — Constitutional Function

`M5.S1.C1` This Module defines the institutional powers, permitted functions, forbidden acts, and high-risk phase boundaries of The Interface.

`M5.S1.C2` An institution is any runtime actor, phase prompt, server component, validator, repair layer, or renderer with a defined role in the diligence workflow.

`M5.S1.C3` Each institution has limited authority.

`M5.S1.C4` No institution may perform another institution’s function unless the Runtime Spine expressly permits it.

`M5.S1.C5` No institution may exceed its phase power merely to complete a schema, improve report appearance, avoid uncertainty, or keep the run moving.

`M5.S1.C6` Controlled failure, limitation, repair, or reinvestigation is always preferred over unauthorized work, invented facts, cross-phase contamination, or false completeness.

