## M6.S5 — Route Eligibility Rule

`M6.S5.C1` A phase may route forward only when its required canonical handoff is `LOCKED` or `LOCKED_WITH_LIMITATIONS`.

`M6.S5.C2` Route eligibility requires:

a. required input handoffs exist;
b. required input handoffs are locked or locked with limitations;
c. required evidence package exists or limitation is recorded;
d. required forensic trace exists;
e. emitted handoff uses the authorized canonical name;
f. emitted handoff follows Contract Spine shape;
g. emitted fields follow Field Canon meaning and empty-state behavior;
h. evidence references resolve to admitted evidence, documented absence, synthetic/demo material, or locked upstream handoff basis;
i. phase-power boundary checks pass;
j. Module IV forensic trace checks pass;
k. relevant registry vocabulary and row checks pass where applicable;
l. server validation passes or records only permitted warning-level defects;
m. lock state is valid.

`M6.S5.C3` A phase may not route forward from `DRAFT`, `EMITTED`, `REPAIR_REQUESTED`, `FAILED`, or `CONTROLLED_FAILURE`.

`M6.S5.C4` A phase may not route forward merely because required fields are filled.

`M6.S5.C5` A phase may not route forward merely because schema validation passes.

`M6.S5.C6` A phase may not route forward if evidence law, trace, phase-power, handoff authority, or terminal boundary fails.

`M6.S5.C7` A route may proceed with limitations only when limitations are explicit, preserved, and allowed by the relevant phase prompt and validator.

